Riddle solved: That's why we can't tickle ourselves
A kind of brake in the cerebrum prevents people from being able to tickle themselves. Scientists at the Humboldt University in Berlin discovered this with the help of experiments on rats, as they announced on Thursday evening. Progress has also been made on the question of why children defend themselves so violently against tickling, only to ask for more.
It showed, he said, why only the approach of a tickling hand causes a layer in the cerebrum ebrum, which causes laughter in the expectation of tickling.
According to the data, earlier research showed that rats react with " laughter " in the ultrasound range when tickled by humans. This " laughter " is mediated by the part of the cerebral cortex, which serves the central processing of haptic perception.
Laughter is suppressed during self-contact
Until now, it was previously assumed that the brain could distinguish between self-touch and touch by others - that is why people cannot tickle themselves. However, the Berlin researchers now found in the experiments experiments on the rats that the laughter as well the activity of the relevant area of the cerebral cortex are suppressed during a self-touch. This is also the case when living beings clean themselves. However, during the foreign touch and the tickling by the scientists, the activity in the brain and the impulse to laugh had been increased.
But if the self-touch and the touch of others happen at the same time, laughter is also suppressed. This indicates that the brain of the rat could not distinguish between the self-touch and the touch of others. The new findings suggested that people cannot ticktickle themselves because the self-touch activated a brake in the cerebrum.
The rats and rats were also trained to tickle themselves. Thus, they sometimes broke this initiation early in the experiment, showed escape behavior or or rigidity. This ambivalence is similar to the behavior of children. The ambivalence of tickling is a behavioral reaction that is the same in rats and humans.
