Attention: NEVER charge smartphone wirelessly
Practical but harmful
Inductive technology via Qi standard is extremely practical but should not be used.
Since several new smartphones have recently come on the market that support wireless charging and sell very very well - above all the new iPhone 11 models, we would like to recall a study from the beginning of July. Although wireless charging of mobile devices is extremely practical, but not necessarily recommended.
Higher temperature increases battery
Researchers warn against wireless charging of smartphones. According to the findings of the Univerity of Warwick this is extremely harmful for the devices. The reason for this is the significantly greater heat generation. If a mobile phone is charged charged by cable, the battery heats up to 27 degrees within three hours. With charging, however, the researchers have measured always than 30 degrees even with perfect alignment of the smartphone on the charging pad. In case the phone is slightly next to the coil, the temperature rises even higher. In addition, the power power of the charging pad also increases, which in turn increases the power consumption.
Capacity and lifetime
According to the researchers, temperature is a decisive factor for the durability of batteries. Here, every single degree plays a role. When charging with higher temperatures, the battery not only only loses its capacity, but also does not hold it so for as long time. Thus, the lifespan is shorter. Therefore, the researchers recommend that you always charge the smartphone via a cable. Since a battery replacement in modern smartphones is always associated with high costs, this should be a helpful hint. Apple has recently increased the cost of a battery replacement even again - for all iPhones.

The technology is extremely convenient here: Simply place the device on a corresponding charging pad - these have now even been installed in many restaurants, airports, hotels and cars - and the battery is charged without the hassle clutter of cables and laborious plug umumbling. Since Qi (stands for inductive energy transmission) is a global standard, in which even Apple participates as an exception, there are hardly any restrictions. Nevertheless, according to the researchers, the technology should only be used in exceptional cases.
