Aegean: Baby and four other children drown in boat accident
While capsizing a refugee boat in the Aegean, a baby and four other children drowned. Altogether seven people died in the accident, according to the Greek Coast Guard on Friday. The nationalities are still unclear.
The boat sank near the Greek island of Inousses, which lies between the island of Chios and the Turkish mainland. Four children, three women and five men were rescued.
Hundreds of migrants from Turkey are currently travelling to the Greek islands in the east of the Aegean Sea. According to information from the United Nations Refugee Agency (UNHCR), 174 people were killed on this route last year. Federal Minister of the Interior Horst Seehofer has now announced that he intends to visit both countries.
Together with his French colleague and the responsible EU Commissioner, he wanted to " find out about the state of the refugee situation in Turkey " said SeSeehofer on Friday. Afterwards, he wanted to learn more about the " administrative problems of the Greeks " in Athens in order to be able to cope with them.
A spokeswoman for the EU Commission on Friday confirmed Seehofer's planned trip with EU Home Affairs Commissioner Dimitris Avramopoulos and France's Interior Minister Christophe Castaner.
In Greece, an unusual number of migrants continue to arrive from Turkey. On Tuesday alone, 654 people travelled to the Greek islands, according to the Greek Ministry of Civil Protection on Wednesday.
Does the deal with Turkey still work?
The increased figures recently gave rise to doubts about the functioning of the EU-Turkey agreement concluded in 2016. This stipulates that the EU can return all refugees and migrants who come via Turkey to the Greek islands illegally. In return, the EU wanted to take in a Syrian refugee from Turkey for every Syrian being deported.
However, the processing of asylum applications is very difficult on the Greek side due to the lack of personnel. According to the 29 400 people are are waiting on Lesbos, Chios Leros, Chios Samos, Leros and Kos. The worst is the situation in Lesbos: 5200 migrants are staying in a camp with a capacity for 650 people.
Never before since the EU-Turkey Compact on Refugees entered into force in March 2016 have there there been so many, reported the state broadcaster.
