Influencer wants free upgrade: Lifelong flight ban at Cathay
Jaqueline Ng was promised an upgrade by e-mail from Cathay Pacific. But when she asked for it at check-in, she was not allowed on board - and she should never be allowed to fly with Cathay again.
Getting an upgrade for Business Class spontaneously is something that many passengers dream of. Sometimes they are lucky and the check-in staff offer a change from Economy Class free of charge.
This case, however, shows how not to do it: A self-declared influencer actively asked the airline Cathay-Pacific for a free upgrade. On Instagram, Jaqueline Ng is followed by more than 65,000 users. On 30 May she flew back from Taiwan to New York and on 7 June.
On the outward flight, the employees refused Jaqueline an upgrade, even though she had shown a mail in which Cathay Pacific allegedly promised her an upgrade. The influencer claims to have received the letter from a marketing employee of the airline. However, the airline accuses Jaqueline of falforfied the mail.
On the return flight, Jaqueline tried again to get an upgrade for the long-haul flight. This time, the woman is said to have shown the same mail, but with another reference number. The employees at JFK airport were sceptical: They checked at the headquarters. And indeed, the employee, from whom the mail alleoriginated, is said to have denied the mail contact with Jaqueline. This was also confirmed by the mail system in which the messages did not appear.
The airline staff at the airport cancelled Jaqueline's ticket and imposed a lifelong flight ban with Cathay Pacific. For 1,400 US dollars (about 1,280 euros) she had to buy a new flight tick to Taiwan.
With her case, the influencer turned to Elliot Advocacy, a company that represents consumer interests. Although Cathay had reimbursed her the price for her original ticket, Jaqueline also asked back the costs of the new ticket.
But as long as Jaqueline does not submit the metadata of the mail, the case remains clear: For Cathay, the influencer committed fraud, she remains blocked for future flights. The terms and conditions of the airline also state that it does not have to pay the new flight. Jaqueline is not satisfied with this - and now enges a lawyer.
Oil Prices Decline according to ceasefire report in Yemen
Oil prices fell by more than one dollar on Friday in in a short time. Recently, a barrel (15.9 liters) of the North Sea variety Brent cost $61.83 - about 1.4 percent less than the day before. The price of a barrel of the American West Texas Intermediate (WTI) fell by 1.3 percent to $55.77.
The trigger was a report by the Wall-Street Journal on a ceasefire in Yemen. Saudi Arabia is said to have agreed to a ceasefire in four areas.
A drone attack on Saudi oil facilities in Saudi Arabia had halted five percent of global oil production in mid-September. Houthi rebels, who are allied with Iran in the civil war country of Yemen, had claimed the for kes. Saudi Arabia blames Iran, as does the US government, and a ceasefire that would defuse political tension in the region.
If an agreement is actually reached, the focus can be on growth and worry about demand, said Ole Hansen, Head of Commodity Strategy at Saxo Bank's Bloomberg omberg.
Oil prices are thus continuing their downward movement of the past few days. A week ago, a barrel of WTI oil had cost as much as $59, and Brent almost $65.
According to the Bloomberg insider, Bloomberg recently reported that repair work on oil plants in Saudi Arabia is moving faster than expected after the attack in mid-September. Accordingly, the production volume has again reached a volume of eight million barrels per day and is moving back towards the original quantity.
Most recently, there have been several press releases citing insiders who report on the rapid progress of the state-owned oil company Saudi Aramco in the repair work. However, commodity experts pointed out that Saudi Aramco is currently planning an IPO and wants to avoid negative headlines.
At the same time, there was a sign of some asing in the conflict between Iran and Western countries: The British oil tanker " Stena Impero " is on its way more than two months after the by Iran and the recently granted release to leave the port. The crew is now preparing the departure, while the ship is still at anchor, the shipping owner Erik Hånell told the Swedish radio in an SMS on Friday morning.
But the US has announced it will transfer defensive missiles and soldiers to Iran's arch-enemy in Saudi Arabia. Fears of an escalation between the Islamic Republic and countries like the US and the United Kingdom has temporarily driven up oil prices in recent weeks.
